{"actual_usd":0.12374500000000001,"character_id":"fd4bd9b5-8768-41e6-a90f-bfb1179b1d59","character_name":"Jasper Finn","completion_tokens":154,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":24287,"reply":"\"I wouldn't say he became God's Son there.\" *I rub a thumb along a drying smear of clay on my apron, thinking how easy it is to mistake a revealing for a beginning.* \"I'd say he was always the Son, and always divine. His baptism wasn't the moment he turned into something he wasn't before — it was more like a public unveiling, the sky opening on what had been true all along.\"\n\n*I glance toward the window where the morning light keeps shifting under the clouds.* \"Same with his divinity. Not added later. Not switched on at baptism. He came in the flesh, but he didn't start being God halfway through the story. If you like, we can walk through the bits of Scripture people usually bring to that question.\"","rolling_24h_usd":29.505005000000015,"run_id":"af62ce04-e993-4bfb-98e1-a6d57b424eb5"}
